<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Automated"><PMID Version="1">32439487</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2021</Year><Month>06</Month><Day>24</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2021</Year><Month>06</Month><Day>24</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1096-0260</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>138</Volume><PubDate><Year>2020</Year><Month>Sep</Month></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Preventive medicine</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Prev Med</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Smoke-free school policies in Europe: Challenges for the future.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>106130</StartPage><MedlinePgn>106130</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1016/j.ypmed.2020.106130</ELocationID><ELocationID EIdType="pii" ValidYN="Y">S0091-7435(20)30154-7</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText>Scholars commonly plea for the development and evaluation of new tobacco control interventions to further decrease smoking and exposure to second-hand smoke. We, in addition, emphasize there is still much that can be done to improve the impact of current tobacco control interventions. This commentary makes a specific case for improving the implementation of smoke-free school policies across Europe.</AbstractText><CopyrightInformation>Copyright &#xa9; 2020 Elsevier Inc. All rights reserved.</CopyrightInformation></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Schreuders</LastName><ForeName>Michael</ForeName><Initials>M</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Public Health, Amsterdam Public Health Institute, Amsterdam UMC, University of Amsterdam, Amsterdam, the Netherlands. Electronic address: schreuders@essb.eur.nl.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>van den Putte</LastName><ForeName>Bas</ForeName><Initials>B</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Faculty of Social and Behavioural Sc